---
import { readFileSync } from 'fs';
import { resolve } from 'path';

let version = '7.6.0';
try {
  const rootspecJson = JSON.parse(readFileSync(resolve('.rootspec.json'), 'utf-8'));
  version = rootspecJson.version ?? version;
} catch (_) {}
---
<section
  data-test="hero-section"
  class="py-20 px-6 max-w-4xl mx-auto"
>
  <div class="mb-6">
    <span
      data-test="version-badge"
      class="font-mono text-xs px-2 py-1 rounded"
      style="background-color: var(--color-code-bg); color: var(--color-text-muted); border: 1px solid var(--color-border);"
    >
      v{version}
    </span>
  </div>

  <h1
    data-test="hero-tagline"
    class="font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl font-light leading-tight mb-6"
    style="color: var(--color-text);"
  >
    When code and specs can be generated trivially,<br/>
    <em>validation is the real value.</em>
  </h1>

  <p
    data-test="hero-description"
    class="text-lg md:text-xl font-sans max-w-2xl leading-relaxed mb-10"
    style="color: var(--color-text-muted);"
  >
    RootSpec is a specification language for software where philosophy guides implementation, never vice versa.
    It captures human intent in a structured, executable hierarchy — then validates that every line of code satisfies that intent.
  </p>

  <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4">
    <a
      href="https://github.com/rootspec/rootspec"
      class="px-5 py-2.5 rounded font-sans text-sm font-medium no-underline transition-opacity"
      style="background-color: var(--color-accent); color: white;"
    >
      Get started →
    </a>
    <a
      href="#spec-wizard"
      class="px-5 py-2.5 rounded font-sans text-sm font-medium no-underline transition-colors"
      style="border: 1px solid var(--color-border); color: var(--color-text);"
    >
      Spec your idea
    </a>
  </div>
</section>
